answers.body_markdown:
You should await asynchronous calls to get results:  

    var response = await _userManager.FindByNameAsync(userName);

Also you will need to decorate GetUserName function with `async`

First, don&#39;t block on async tasks. You&#39;re in an async method, so there&#39;s no reason not to actually await the result:

    private async Task&lt;string&gt; GetUserNameAsync(string userName)
    {
        var response = await _userManager.FindByNameAsync(userName);
        return response?.UserName ?? string.Empty;
    }

Then:

    var userName = await GetUserNameAsync(user);

Second, this doesn&#39;t make any sense anyways, as you *already* have the username. You just need to know whether it exists yet or not. As such, you should really have something like?

    public async Task&lt;bool&gt; UserNameExistsAsync(string userName)
    {
        return await _userManager.FindByNameAsync(userName) != null;
    }

Then:

    if (await UserNameExistsAsync(user))
    {
        // do something
    }

And, actually, it would be *better* to use the context directly here, but that might require an additional dependency:

    var userNameExists = await _context.Users.AnyAsync(x =&gt; x.UserName == user);

Regardless, the source of your issue is that when it comes time to call `PasswordSignInAsync`, the value you&#39;re passing in for `userName` could be an empty string, which is not a valid value for that param. Wrapping this call in a conditional  would fix the issue, such that you only run it if the user actually exists.

